<subSubSection id="D43E31B343E77EDCA45C055AC8934EFE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2FD31A8FF9A50B02067F6BC2D25F3FFD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FCACC75DCCEF476F655BFF5CAA7AEF65" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species is named in honour of Professor Wen-Tsai Wang (1926-), a taxonomist at the Institute of Botany, the Chinese Academy of Sciences, who has devoted over 60 years to taxonomic studies of 
<taxonomicName id="581E2ED4114447C6C40120EE33828DFC" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ranunculaceae" genus="Pteris" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Ranunculales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Ranunculaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="897F62EF4962B0EB937DDD06C339F5D6" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Gesneriaceae" genus="Pteris" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Lamiales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Gesneriaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="B9B8832C994E3C2374977D564459B5A4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Boraginaceae" genus="Pteris" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Boraginales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Boraginaceae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="8E92CC815927554304D3F3A46DC96C1D" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Pteris" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Urticaceae</taxonomicName>
and many other families and the floristic research in eastern Asia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8B217900A273FD44E7893C511DFF27F4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="vernacular name">
<paragraph id="F109CE693C476F628A153D0A25D9E21F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Vernacular name.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5EA690543E63F6F454AF54B8C3883B0B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Wen Cai Ying Tao (Chinese).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="38A7A0A34A70CA1ED96C1CEA71309426" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="conservation assessment">
<paragraph id="E1F80536F6D7B23B2B75CAD41F72929B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Conservation assessment.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F3EAECDBE7B3F97B66A02499618942CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
We found 
<taxonomicName id="2A60CF8CF31DB2237C1CC15FF25F5A6B" authorityName="Q. L. Gan, Z. Y. Li &amp; S. Z. Xu" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Prunus wangii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="wangii">
<emphasis id="908A68F25F08E71825B4BF25C6B6952E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Prunus wangii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only in the towns of Quanxi and Tianbao, Hubei Province and estimated the population size to be ca. 20 individuals. The provisional conservation status is Critically Endangered (CR), based on criterion D (number of mature individuals fewer than 50) (
<bibRefCitation id="6976320D5C543CFDF3D1B45B17C2B985" author="Harris, JG" journalOrPublisher="Spring Lake Publishing, Payson" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B2" refString="2022. . http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2022">IUCN 2022</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="24EBDB9121CEBAE0F38C1B5D9A864C61" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="economic uses">
<paragraph id="7F02CA8904B3D7CD1F48D7CBB0F0FB9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Economic uses.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F730669B9074D986BCCCBD2BE4576A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
There are more than 140 species of flowering cherries widely distributed in the Northern Hemisphere, but species blossoming in February are rare. Two species, 
<taxonomicName id="57FEF823EE8E4227C1ACC80BE30CF91F" genus="P." lsidName="P. pseudocerasus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="pseudocerasus">
<emphasis id="394849352A9F7323BA1AF2337FB81EA8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. pseudocerasus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Lindl. and 
<taxonomicName id="5444EDD65083B1EE826A122565C06469" genus="P." lsidName="P. campanulata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="campanulata">
<emphasis id="5BBD2F88D622AD428DA73DBCF7A6D6E8" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. campanulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Maxim., have been used as important breeding materials of flowering cherries with early spring blooms since their introduction into Japan (
<bibRefCitation id="5EACEC6874BF274AAD68FF0DAD0BAD6F" author="Ohwi, J" journalOrPublisher="IIb, Kodansha, Tokyo" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B6" refString="Ohwi, J, Ohta, Y, 1973. Flowering Cherries of Japan. Heibonsha, Tokyo." title="Flowering Cherries of Japan. Heibonsha, Tokyo." year="1973">Ohwi and Ohta 1973</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="FEDB6153BEF90D885CCE760C4483E60A" author="Ohba, H" editor="Iwatsuki, K" journalOrPublisher="IIb, Kodansha, Tokyo" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="128 - 144" refId="B5" refString="Ohba, H, 2001. Cerasus. In: Iwatsuki, K, Boufford, DE, Ohba, H, Eds., Flora of Japan, vol. IIb, Kodansha, Tokyo: 128 - 144" title="Cerasus." volumeTitle="Flora of Japan, vol." year="2001">Ohba 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="D768C7F3A0EBD3417254F28B75D0CDCE" author="Wang, XR" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Integrative Plant Biology" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="B8" refString="Wang, XR, 2014. An Illustrated Monograph of Cherry Cultivars in China. Science Press, Beijing. [in Chinese]" title="An Illustrated Monograph of Cherry Cultivars in China. Science Press, Beijing. [in Chinese]" year="2014">Wang 2014</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="CD3FB125C4D04D6587022E1A833D7C66" authorityName="Q. L. Gan, Z. Y. Li &amp; S. Z. Xu" authorityYear="2022" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Prunus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Prunus wangii" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="wangii">
<emphasis id="C620512866A78C0B66FB33CCDCB3CFE4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Prunus wangii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will provide a new breeding material for early flowering ornamental cherries. The timber of this species is hard and was used to make chopping blocks and furniture by the local people. The mature fruit is red, sweet or slightly bitter and is eaten by the local people.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
